### What version of Bun is running?

1.4.0-canary.1+6bb513507

### What platform is your computer?

Darwin 25.5.0 arm64 arm

### What steps can reproduce the bug?

This script creates a reproduction:
```
mkdir bun-html-splitting-repro && cd bun-html-splitting-repro
bun init -y
bun add react react-dom

cat > generate.js << 'EOF'
import { mkdirSync, writeFileSync } from "node:fs";

const PAGE_COUNT = 20;
const HOOK_COUNT = 20;
const UTIL_COUNT = 20;

mkdirSync("src/shared", { recursive: true });
mkdirSync("src/pages", { recursive: true });

for (let h = 0; h < HOOK_COUNT; h++) {
  const utilDep = h % UTIL_COUNT;
  writeFileSync(
    `src/shared/hook${h}.ts`,
    `import { useEffect, useState } from "react";
import { util${utilDep} } from "./util${utilDep}";

export function useHook${h}(seed: number) {
  const [value, setValue] = useState(util${utilDep}(seed));
  useEffect(() => {
    const id = setInterval(() => setValue((v) => v + 1), 10_000);
    return () => clearInterval(id);
  }, []);
  return value * ${h + 1};
}
`,
  );
}

for (let u = 0; u < UTIL_COUNT; u++) {
  writeFileSync(`src/shared/util${u}.ts`, `export function util${u}(input: number) {\n  return input + ${u};\n}\n`);
}

const importLines = [];
const renderLines = [];

for (let p = 0; p < PAGE_COUNT; p++) {
  const hookIdx = [...new Set([p % HOOK_COUNT, (p * 3 + 1) % HOOK_COUNT])];
  const utilIdx = [...new Set([(p * 5 + 2) % UTIL_COUNT, (p * 7 + 3) % UTIL_COUNT])];

  const hookImports = hookIdx.map((h) => `import { useHook${h} } from "../shared/hook${h}";`).join("\n");
  const utilImports = utilIdx.map((u) => `import { util${u} } from "../shared/util${u}";`).join("\n");
  const hookCalls = hookIdx.map((h) => `useHook${h}(${p})`).join(" + ");
  const utilCalls = utilIdx.map((u) => `util${u}(${p})`).join(" + ");

  writeFileSync(
    `src/pages/Page${p}.tsx`,
    `${hookImports}\n${utilImports}\n\nexport default function Page${p}() {\n  const hookTotal = ${hookCalls || "0"};\n  const utilTotal = ${utilCalls || "0"};\n  return <p>Page ${p}: {hookTotal + utilTotal}</p>;\n}\n`,
  );

  importLines.push(`const Page${p} = lazy(() => import("./pages/Page${p}"));`);
  renderLines.push(`      <Page${p} />`);
}

writeFileSync(
  "src/App.tsx",
  `import { lazy, Suspense } from "react";\n\n${importLines.join("\n")}\n\nexport default function App() {\n  return (\n    <Suspense fallback={<div>loading</div>}>\n${renderLines.join("\n")}\n    </Suspense>\n  );\n}\n`,
);

writeFileSync(
  "src/main.tsx",
  `import { createRoot } from "react-dom/client";\nimport App from "./App";\n\nconsole.log("MAIN_ENTRY_EXECUTED");\n\nconst el = document.getElementById("root");\nif (!el) throw new Error("no #root element");\ncreateRoot(el).render(<App />);\n`,
);

writeFileSync(
  "index.html",
  `<!doctype html>\n<html>\n  <head>\n    <meta charset="utf-8" />\n    <title>repro</title>\n  </head>\n  <body>\n    <div id="root"></div>\n    <script type="module" src="./src/main.tsx"></script>\n  </body>\n</html>\n`,
);

console.log(`generated ${PAGE_COUNT} pages, ${HOOK_COUNT} hooks, ${UTIL_COUNT} utils`);
EOF

cat > build.ts << 'EOF'
import { basename, resolve } from "node:path";

const outdir = resolve(import.meta.dirname, "dist");

const result = await Bun.build({
  entrypoints: [resolve(import.meta.dirname, "index.html")],
  outdir,
  target: "browser",
  minify: true,
  splitting: true,
  publicPath: "/",
});

if (!result.success) {
  for (const log of result.logs) console.error(log);
  process.exit(1);
}

const entryScript = result.outputs.find((o) => o.kind === "entry-point" && o.path.endsWith(".js"));
if (!entryScript) throw new Error("no JS entry-point in build output");

const html = await Bun.file(resolve(outdir, "index.html")).text();
const scriptSrc = /<script[^>]*\bsrc="([^"]+)"/.exec(html)?.[1];
if (!scriptSrc) throw new Error("no <script src> in generated index.html");

const trueEntry = `/${basename(entryScript.path)}`;
console.log(`result.outputs entry-point : ${trueEntry}`);
console.log(`index.html <script src>    : ${scriptSrc}`);
console.log(scriptSrc !== trueEntry ? "MISMATCH — bug reproduced" : "match — not reproduced this run");
EOF

rm -rf src dist
bun generate.js
bun build.ts
```

### What is the expected behavior?

`index.html`'s <script type="module" src="..."> should point at the same file
that Bun.build()'s own result.outputs reports as the entry-point chunk (the
one containing the app's actual entry code).

### What do you see instead?

The two disagree. `index.html`'s <script src> references a JS chunk that does
NOT contain the entry code (confirmed by grepping for a marker string logged
only from main.tsx), while the chunk result.outputs correctly identifies as
kind: "entry-point" is never referenced from the HTML at all.

Output from the repro above:

  result.outputs entry-point : /chunk-rnccfznz.js
  index.html <script src>    : /chunk-qrv9vwj0.js
  MISMATCH — bug reproduced

Reproduces on every clean run (verified 15+ times). In a real app this means
the browser executes the wrong module graph on page load — no createRoot()
call ever runs, so the page renders a permanently blank <div id="root">
with no console errors or build warnings of any kind.

### Additional information

The trigger is the reachability structure among shared modules under
code-splitting, not raw entry count. In this repro's shape (each page
importing 2 of a shared pool of hooks and 2 of a shared pool of utils),
9 pages never reproduces and 10+ pages always reproduces once the shared
pool size is 20. At a shared-pool size of 8, no page count reproduces it.

Root cause: `get_js_chunk_for_html` in src/bundler/Chunk.rs pairs the HTML
chunk to the first JS chunk in `chunks` whose `entry_point_id` matches, with
no check that the match is unique. When more than one chunk carries the
html's `entry_point_id`, whichever comes first in iteration order wins —
not necessarily the actual entry chunk.

# `perf_hooks`: `eventLoopUtilization()` returns all-zeros and `process.memoryUsage().heapUsed` is ~0 (breaks `@fastify/under-pressure` load shedding)

### What version of Bun is running?

1.3.14 (Linux x64)

### What platform is your computer?

Linux x86_64 (Ubuntu, kernel 6.14, containerized)

### What steps can reproduce the bug?

Two `node:perf_hooks` APIs that load-shedding libraries depend on return placeholder
values under Bun while working under Node. Minimal repro — run under both runtimes:

```js
// repro.mjs
import { performance, monitorEventLoopDelay } from 'node:perf_hooks';

const runtime = typeof Bun !== 'undefined' ? `Bun ${Bun.version}` : `Node ${process.version}`;
const blockFor = (ms) => { const s = Date.now(); while (Date.now() - s < ms) Math.sqrt(Math.random()); };

const eluStart = performance.eventLoopUtilization();
const h = monitorEventLoopDelay({ resolution: 10 });
h.enable();

setTimeout(() => {
  blockFor(300);                       // keep the loop busy so utilization should be > 0
  setTimeout(() => {
    const elu = performance.eventLoopUtilization(eluStart);
    const mem = process.memoryUsage();
    console.log(`${runtime}`);
    console.log('eventLoopUtilization:', elu);
    console.log('memoryUsage.heapUsed:', mem.heapUsed, 'heapTotal:', mem.heapTotal, 'rss:', mem.rss);
    process.exit(0);
  }, 50);
}, 200);
```

```
node repro.mjs
bun  repro.mjs
```

### What is the expected behavior?

Same as Node — `eventLoopUtilization()` reports a real active/idle ratio, and
`memoryUsage().heapUsed` reports real heap usage:

```
Node v22.22.2
eventLoopUtilization: { idle: 248.83, active: 300.05, utilization: 0.5466 }
memoryUsage.heapUsed: 4127232 heapTotal: 6918144 rss: 52342784
```

### What do you see instead?

`eventLoopUtilization()` is a stub that always returns zeros, and `heapUsed`/`heapTotal`
are effectively unpopulated (`rss` is fine):

```
Bun 1.3.14
eventLoopUtilization: { idle: 0, active: 0, utilization: 0 }
memoryUsage.heapUsed: 388155 heapTotal: 880640 rss: 43577344
```

So, per signal:

| `perf_hooks` API                                 | Node v22        | Bun 1.3.14              |
| ------------------------------------------------ | --------------- | ----------------------- |
| `performance.eventLoopUtilization().utilization` | real (e.g. 0.55)| **0 (always)**          |
| `process.memoryUsage().heapUsed`                 | real (~4 MB)    | **~0 / unpopulated**    |
| `process.memoryUsage().rss`                      | real            | real ✅                 |
| `monitorEventLoopDelay().mean` / `.max`          | real            | real ✅                 |

### Additional context

Impact: [`@fastify/under-pressure`](https://github.com/fastify/under-pressure) — the
standard Fastify load-shedding plugin — decides when to return `503` from exactly these
signals (`maxEventLoopUtilization`, `maxHeapUsedBytes`, `maxEventLoopDelay`,
`maxRssBytes`). Under Bun, `maxEventLoopUtilization` and `maxHeapUsedBytes` silently never
fire, so an operator who configures either believes they have overload protection they do
not actually have. (`maxRssBytes` and `maxEventLoopDelay` do work, so a Bun-safe config
must rely on those.) `monitorEventLoopDelay()` itself works correctly — it captures a 300ms
block as `max ≈ 297ms`, matching Node — so this report is specifically about
`eventLoopUtilization()` and `memoryUsage().heapUsed`.

Both `performance.eventLoopUtilization` and `process.memoryUsage` are documented as
Node-compatible, so returning placeholder zeros (rather than throwing `not implemented`)
makes the gap hard to detect — callers just get a value that is silently always under
threshold.

### What version of Bun is running?

1.3.14 (also reproduces on the arm64 Linux base image `oven/bun`)

### What platform is your computer?

macOS (arm64) and Linux (arm64)

### What steps can reproduce the bug?

An exception thrown **synchronously from a socket `'data'` listener** should surface as an `uncaughtException` — that is what Node.js does, regardless of whether the socket has an `'error'` listener (a socket `'error'` listener is for *socket* errors, not for exceptions thrown by *other* listeners). Bun instead **routes the thrown exception to the socket's own `'error'` listener** when one is registered, so the exception silently disappears.

Minimal, dependency-free repro (`issue1-minimal.mjs`):

```js
import net from "node:net";
import { EventEmitter } from "node:events";

process.on("uncaughtException", (e) => {
  console.log(`uncaughtException REACHED: ${e.message}`);
  process.exit(3);
});

// A second, unrelated emitter with NO 'error' listener — emitting 'error' on it throws
// (the Node "unhandled 'error' event" contract).
const pool = new EventEmitter();

const server = net.createServer((s) => setTimeout(() => s.end("x"), 50));
server.listen(0, () => {
  const c = net.connect(server.address().port);
  c.on("error", () => {});                         // the socket HAS an 'error' listener
  c.on("data", () => {
    pool.emit("error", new Error("thrown from inside a socket 'data' listener"));
  });
});

setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("STILL ALIVE 500ms later — the thrown exception was SWALLOWED");
  process.exit(0);
}, 500);
```

Run on both runtimes:

```
$ node issue1-minimal.mjs
uncaughtException REACHED: thrown from inside a socket 'data' listener   # exit 3

$ bun issue1-minimal.mjs
STILL ALIVE 500ms later — the thrown exception was SWALLOWED             # exit 0
```

If you **remove** the `c.on("error", () => {})` line, Bun propagates correctly (reaches `uncaughtException`). So the swallow only happens when the socket has an `'error'` listener — the thrown value is being delivered to that listener. Adding `c.on("error", e => console.log("socket error handler got:", e.message))` prints the thrown error's message, confirming the misrouting.

### Real-world manifestation (`pg` + PostgreSQL)

This is exactly how `node-postgres` (`pg`) loses an unhandled pool error. `pg` registers an `'error'` listener on its connection socket (`reportStreamError`). When an idle pooled connection's backend goes away (pooler restart, failover, `pg_terminate_backend`), `pg` parses the FATAL message inside the socket `'data'` handler and re-emits `'error'` on the `Pool`. With no `pool.on('error')` listener, Node throws the classic *"Unhandled 'error' event"* and the process exits 1. On Bun the throw is routed to `pg`'s socket `'error'` handler and vanishes — the process stays alive (exit 0) with **no output at all**.

`issue1-pg.mjs` (needs a Postgres; `docker run -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=… -p 55432:5432 postgres:16`):

```
Node v24.14.0 → node:events:486  throw er; // Unhandled 'error' event  (code '57P01')  exit 1
Bun 1.3.14   → "STILL ALIVE 1.5s later — the unhandled pool 'error' was SWALLOWED"      exit 0
```

Deterministic across runs (Bun 3/3 swallow, Node 2/2 crash).

### What is the expected behavior?

An exception thrown by a `'data'` listener propagates as an `uncaughtException` (matching Node.js). A socket `'error'` listener should only receive genuine socket errors, not exceptions thrown by unrelated listeners.

### What do you see instead?

The thrown exception is delivered to the socket's `'error'` listener and never reaches `uncaughtException`, so unhandled errors that crash on Node are silently swallowed on Bun. For pooled DB apps this means a lost connection (which *should* crash-loop or at minimum log) instead continues running against a dead pool with zero diagnostics — and since this is unspecified behavior, a base-image bump can change it.

### Notes on what does NOT reproduce (scoping)

- `new EventEmitter().emit("error", new Error())` at top level **throws** on Bun (correct).
- A direct `throw` inside a socket `'data'` listener **does** reach `uncaughtException` on Bun (correct) — **when the socket has no `'error'` listener**.
- Emitting an unhandled `'error'` on a separate emitter from a `'data'` listener **also** propagates on Bun — **when the socket has no `'error'` listener**.
- The swallow appears specifically when the socket **has** an `'error'` listener.

### What version of Bun is running?

1.3.14

### What platform is your computer?

Linux 7.0.2-6-pve x86_64 x86_64

### What steps can reproduce the bug?

`test.js` inspired from #8079 but using dot product:
```js
import { run, bench } from "mitata";

// Assuming the vectors are of the same length
function cosineDistance(a, b) {
  if (a.length !== b.length) return 0;
  let dot = 0;
  for (let i = 0; i < a.length; i++) dot += a[i] * b[i];
  return dot;
}

// Generate random data for testing
const dimensions = 1536; // Adjust dimensions as needed
const array1 = Array.from({ length: dimensions }, () => Math.random() * 100);
const array2 = Array.from({ length: dimensions }, () => Math.random() * 100);
const float16_1 = new Float16Array(array1);
const float16_2 = new Float16Array(array2);
const float32_1 = new Float32Array(array1);
const float32_2 = new Float32Array(array2);

bench("array", () => {
  cosineDistance(array1, array2);
});

bench("float16", () => {
  cosineDistance(float16_1, float16_2);
});

bench("float32", () => {
  cosineDistance(float32_1, float32_2);
});

await run();
```

### What is the expected behavior?

For `bun` to be on par (or better) than `node`.

### What do you see instead?

`% node test.js ; bun test.js ; node test.js ; bun test.js`
(executed twice in a row just to be sure it's "hot" even though probably `mitata` does that already?)

<img width="910" height="765" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/735fff50-588d-46da-9cfc-9cb8081ee765" />

### Additional information

Also reproduces similarly on 1.3.13 and on different hardware.

### What is the problem this feature would solve?

if a module is all declarations and no top-level code, the minifier can minify everything to a single chained `var`. If there are two modules that are only var-declarations, they can be chained!

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

Have each module result have fields on it like `LastStatementIsVar` and `FirstStatementIsVar` or something, and then in the final linker check those fields on each pair of consecutive modules, and if the first one has `LastStatementIsVar` and the next has `FirstStatementIsVar`, you can just remove the `;` on the first one and change the `var ` of the second one to `,` or something.

Specifically if I have
```js
// main.js
import foo from "./file.js"
import foo2 from "./file2.js"
console.log(foo, foo2);
// file.js
export default "hi";
// file2.js
export default "bye";
```
and I build main.js, I get
```js
var o="hi";var e="bye";console.log(o,e);
```
but it could be
```js
var o="hi",e="bye";console.log(o,e);
```

### What alternatives have you considered?

This can be fixed by running Bun twice, once to produce the bundle, and again to optimize the bundle, but doing it this way obliterates the sourcemaps and I can't figure out how to make it inherit the sourcemap.

### What version of Bun is running?
Reproduced on **1.3.14** (latest) and 1.3.13, Linux x64. Built-in `Bun.sql` (no external driver).

### What platform is your computer?
Linux x86_64, PostgreSQL 18.4.

### What steps can reproduce the bug?

With the built-in `Bun.sql` client and the **default `prepare: true`**, a pooled workload that interleaves a prepared `SELECT` and a prepared `INSERT` under pool oversubscription (concurrency ≫ `max`) **deadlocks when you stop issuing new queries and await the last in-flight ones**. The steady-state flow is fine on 1.3.14; the hang appears at **drain / wind-down** — `Promise.allSettled(workers)` (or any code awaiting the final queries) never resolves.

> Note: a test that exits on a timer *without* awaiting the workers hides this — it reports success because queries flowed during the window. You must `await` every query, exactly like real code (`const rows = await sql\`…\``, `await Promise.all([...])`, or a graceful pool drain).

Self-contained repro (no deps):

```ts
// PG=postgres://user:pass@localhost:5432/db  bun repro.ts
// PREPARE=false bun repro.ts   # workaround: drains fine
import { SQL } from "bun";

const URL = process.env.PG || "postgres://postgres:postgres@localhost:5432/postgres";
const POOL = 20, CONCURRENCY = 200, ROWS = 50_000, RUN_MS = 12_000, DRAIN_TIMEOUT_MS = 15_000;
const PREPARE = process.env.PREPARE !== "false"; // default true

const s = new SQL(URL, { max: 1 });
await s`DROP TABLE IF EXISTS bun_repro`;
await s`CREATE TABLE bun_repro (id bigserial primary key, n int not null, t text not null)`;
await s.unsafe(`INSERT INTO bun_repro(n,t) SELECT (random()*1000)::int,'x' FROM generate_series(1,${ROWS})`);
await s.end();

const db = new SQL(URL, { max: POOL, prepare: PREPARE });
await db`SELECT 1`;
const SEL = "SELECT id, n, t FROM bun_repro WHERE id = $1";
const INS = "INSERT INTO bun_repro(n, t) VALUES ($1, $2)";
let running = true, done = 0;
async function worker() {
  while (running) {
    const p = Math.random() < 0.85
      ? db.unsafe(SEL, [1 + ((Math.random()*ROWS)|0)])
      : db.unsafe(INS, [(Math.random()*1000)|0, "x"]);
    await p; done++;
  }
}
const workers = Array.from({ length: CONCURRENCY }, worker);
setTimeout(() => { running = false; }, RUN_MS); // stop -> begin drain

const drained  = Promise.allSettled(workers).then(() => "DRAINED");
const timedOut = new Promise<string>(r => setTimeout(() => r("HANG_AT_DRAIN"), RUN_MS + DRAIN_TIMEOUT_MS));
const verdict  = await Promise.race([drained, timedOut]);
console.log(`Bun ${Bun.version} prepare:${PREPARE} conc=${CONCURRENCY} pool=${POOL} done=${done} -> ${verdict}`);
process.exit(verdict === "DRAINED" ? 0 : 1);
```

### What is the expected behavior?
After `running = false`, each worker's final in-flight query resolves and `Promise.allSettled` completes → `DRAINED`.

### What do you see instead?
```
Bun 1.3.14 prepare:true  conc=200 pool=20 done=NNNNNN -> HANG_AT_DRAIN
Bun 1.3.14 prepare:false conc=200 pool=20 done=NNNNNN -> DRAINED
```
With the default `prepare:true` the drain never completes. Confirmed 3/3 on 1.3.14; `prepare:false` drains cleanly 2/2.

**Server-side evidence (the stall is client-side).** Mid-run, `pg_stat_activity` is healthy (backends `active`). At drain, all pooled backends sit:
```
 state | wait_event_type | wait_event
-------+-----------------+------------
 idle  | Client          | ClientRead   (×20)
```
i.e. Postgres has answered and is waiting for the next command — Bun never resolves the JS promises for those final queries. **No query errors occur.**

### Isolation (what triggers it)
Needs **all three** together:
1. `prepare: true` (default) — `prepare: false` drains fine.
2. concurrency ≫ pool `max` (oversubscription) — concurrency ≤ max is fine.
3. the workload interleaves a **read** and a **write** — SELECT-only, INSERT-only, or two distinct SELECTs are all fine; `SELECT + INSERT` (and `SELECT + INSERT … RETURNING`) hang, so it is the **write in the mix**, not a “no RowDescription” shape.

Version note: on **1.3.13** this triggers readily, even at small pools and mid-stream (e.g. `max=2, concurrency=100` wedges almost immediately). On **1.3.14** the steady flow is robust but the **drain-time** hang above remains.

### Workarounds
1. `new SQL(url, { prepare: false })` (confirmed). Caveat: `Date` params serialize incorrectly with `prepare:false` (#29010) — pass ISO strings.
2. Don’t oversubscribe: `max ≥ concurrency`, or bound in-flight ≤ `max`.
3. Use `postgres.js` / `node-postgres` for mixed read/write hot paths (both drain fine here).

### Possibly related
#22505 (pipeline error-recovery), #16844 / #17173 (prepared-statement race under concurrency), #30646 (queued/in-flight queries stranded on a connection not re-dispatched). This case has **no** query error and survives to 1.3.14, so it appears to be a residual prepared-statement/pipeline dispatch desync that surfaces specifically at pipeline wind-down under pool starvation.
